# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: parallel-complexity
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] In computer architecture, **Amdahl's law** (or **Amdahl's argument**) is a formula limiting the speedup of a task as resources are added to the system executing that task.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] It is named after computer scientist Gene Amdahl, and was presented at the American Federation of Information Processing Societies (AFIPS) Spring Joint Computer Conference in 1967.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] Amdahl's law is often used in parallel computing to predict the theoretical speedup when using multiple processors.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] The ${\text{Speedup}}_{\text{overall}}$ is frequently much lower than one might expect.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] So, despite a massive improvement in one section, the overall benefit is quite small.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] In another example, if the programmer optimizes a section that accounts for 99% of the execution time (i.e. ${\text{Time}}_{\text{optimized}}$ of 0.99) with a speedup factor of 100 (i.e. ${\text{Speedup}}_{\text{optimized}}$ of 100), the ${\text{Speedup}}_{\text{overall}}$ only reaches 50.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] This indicates that half of the potential performance gain ( ${\text{Speedup}}_{\text{overall}}$ will reach 100 if 100% of the execution time is covered) is lost due to the remaining 1% of execution time that was not improved.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] An example is a computer program that processes files.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] A part of that program may scan the directory of the disk and create a list of files internally in memory.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] After that, another part of the program passes each file to a separate thread for processing.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] The part that scans the directory and creates the file list cannot be sped up on a parallel computer, but the part that processes the files can.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] The execution time of the whole task before the improvement of the resources of the system is denoted as T .
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] It includes the execution time of the part that would not benefit from the improvement of the resources and the execution time of the one that would benefit from it.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] The fraction of the execution time of the task that would benefit from the improvement of the resources is denoted by p .
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] The one concerning the part that would not benefit from it is therefore $1-p$ .
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] It is the execution of the part that benefits from the improvement of the resources that is accelerated by the factor s after the improvement of the resources.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] If 30% of the execution time may be the subject of a speedup, *p* will be 0.3; if the improvement makes the affected part twice as fast, *s* will be 2.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] For example, assume that we are given a serial task which is split into four consecutive parts, whose percentages of execution time are *p*1 = 0.11, *p*2 = 0.18, *p*3 = 0.23, and *p*4 = 0.48 respectively.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] Then we are told that the 1st part is not sped up, so *s*1 = 1, while the 2nd part is sped up 5 times, so *s*2 = 5, the 3rd part is sped up 20 times, so *s*3 = 20, and the 4th part is sped up 1.6 times, so *s*4 = 1.6.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] Notice how the 5 times and 20 times speedup on the 2nd and 3rd parts respectively don't have much effect on the overall speedup when the 4th part (48% of the execution time) is accelerated by only 1.6 times.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] Therefore, making part *A* to run 2 times faster is better than making part *B* to run 5 times faster.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] When $s=1$ , we have $S_{\text{latency}}(O,s)=1$ , meaning that the speedup is measured with respect to the execution time after the non-parallelizable part is optimized.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] Next, we consider the case wherein the non-parallelizable part is reduced by a factor of $O'$ , and the parallelizable part is correspondingly increased.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] Amdahl's law is often conflated with the law of diminishing returns, whereas only a special case of applying Amdahl's law demonstrates the law of diminishing returns.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] If one picks optimally (in terms of the achieved speedup) what is to be improved, then one will see monotonically decreasing improvements as one improves.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] If, however, one picks non-optimally, after improving a sub-optimal component and moving on to improve a more optimal component, one can see an increase in the return.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] Note that it is often rational to improve a system in an order that is "non-optimal" in this sense, given that some improvements are more difficult or require larger development time than others.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] Amdahl's law does represent the law of diminishing returns if one is considering what sort of return one gets by adding more processors to a machine, if one is running a fixed-size computation that will use all available processors to their capacity.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] Each new processor added to the system will add less usable power than the previous one.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] Each time one doubles the number of processors the speedup ratio will diminish, as the total throughput heads toward the limit of 1/(1 − *p*).
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] This analysis neglects other potential bottlenecks such as memory bandwidth and I/O bandwidth.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] If these resources do not scale with the number of processors, then merely adding processors provides even lower returns.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] An implication of Amdahl's law is that to speed up real applications which have both serial and parallel portions, heterogeneous computing techniques are required.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] There are novel speedup and energy consumption models based on a more general representation of heterogeneity, referred to as the normal form heterogeneity, that support a wide range of heterogeneous many-core architectures.
[src:parallel-complexity/amdahl-s-law] These modelling methods aim to predict system power efficiency and performance ranges, and facilitates research and development at the hardware and system software levels.
[src:parallel-complexity/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] In computer science, **analysis of parallel algorithms** is the process of finding the computational complexity of algorithms executed in parallel – the amount of time, storage, or other resources needed to execute them.
[src:parallel-complexity/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] In many respects, analysis of parallel algorithms is similar to the analysis of sequential algorithms, but is generally more involved because one must reason about the behavior of multiple cooperating threads of execution.
[src:parallel-complexity/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] One of the primary goals of parallel analysis is to understand how a parallel algorithm's use of resources (speed, space, etc.) changes as the number of processors is changed.
[src:parallel-complexity/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] A so-called work-time (WT) (sometimes called work-depth, or work-span) framework was originally introduced by Shiloach and Vishkin for conceptualizing and describing parallel algorithms.
[src:parallel-complexity/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] In the WT framework, a parallel algorithm is first described in terms of parallel rounds.
[src:parallel-complexity/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] For each round, the operations to be performed are characterized, but several issues can be suppressed.
[src:parallel-complexity/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] For example, the number of operations at each round need not be clear, processors need not be mentioned and any information that may help with the assignment of processors to jobs need not be accounted for.
[src:parallel-complexity/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] Second, the suppressed information is provided.
[src:parallel-complexity/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] The inclusion of the suppressed information is guided by the proof of a scheduling theorem due to Brent, which is explained later in this article.
[src:parallel-complexity/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] The WT framework is useful since while it can greatly simplify the initial description of a parallel algorithm, inserting the details suppressed by that initial description is often not very difficult.
[src:parallel-complexity/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] For example, the WT framework was adopted as the basic presentation framework in the parallel algorithms books (for the parallel random-access machine PRAM model) and, as well as in the class notes .
[src:parallel-complexity/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] The overview below explains how the WT framework can be used for analyzing more general parallel algorithms, even when their description is not available within the WT framework.
[src:parallel-complexity/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] Suppose computations are executed on a machine that has p processors.
[src:parallel-complexity/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] Let Tp denote the time that expires between the start of the computation and its end.
[src:parallel-complexity/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] Analysis of parallel algorithms is usually carried out under the assumption that an unbounded number of processors is available.
[src:parallel-complexity/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] This is unrealistic, but not a problem, since any computation that can run in parallel on N processors can be executed on *p* < *N* processors by letting each processor execute multiple units of work.
[src:parallel-complexity/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] showing that the span (depth) *T*∞ and the work *T*1 together provide reasonable bounds on the computation time.
[src:parallel-complexity/cost-efficiency] For example, an algorithm that can be solved in $O(n)$ time using the best known sequential algorithm and $O\left({\frac {n}{p}}\right)$ in a parallel computer with p processors will be considered cost efficient.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] In computational complexity theory, a decision problem is **P-complete** (complete for the complexity class **P**) if it is in **P** and every problem in **P** can be reduced to it by an appropriate reduction.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] The notion of **P-complete** decision problems is useful in the analysis of which problems are difficult to parallelize effectively and which problems are difficult to solve in limited space, specifically when stronger notions of reducibility than polytime-reducibility are considered.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] The specific type of reduction used varies and may affect the exact set of problems.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] Generically, reductions stricter than polynomial-time reductions are used, since all languages in **P** (except the empty language and the language of all strings) are **P**-complete under polynomial-time reductions.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] If we use **NC** reductions, that is, reductions that can operate in polylogarithmic time on a parallel computer with a polynomial number of processors, then all **P**-complete problems lie outside **NC** and so cannot be effectively parallelized, under the unproven assumption that **NC** ≠ **P**.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] If we use the stronger log-space reduction, this remains true, but additionally we learn that all **P**-complete problems lie outside L under the weaker unproven assumption that **L** ≠ **P**.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] In this latter case the set **P**-complete may be smaller.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] The class **P**, typically taken to consist of all the "tractable" problems for a sequential computer, contains the class **NC**, which consists of those problems that can be efficiently solved on a parallel computer.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] This is because parallel computers can be simulated on a sequential machine.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] In other words, it is not known whether there are any tractable problems that are inherently sequential.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] Just as it is widely suspected that **P** does not equal **NP**, so it is widely suspected that **NC** does not equal **P**.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] Similarly, the class **L** contains all problems that can be solved by a sequential computer in logarithmic space.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] Such machines run in polynomial time because they can only have a polynomial number of different configurations.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] It is suspected that **L** ≠ **P**; that is, that some problems that can be solved in polynomial time also require more than logarithmic space.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] Similarly to the use of NP-complete problems to analyze the **P** = **NP** question, the **P**-complete problems, viewed as the "probably not parallelizable" or "probably inherently sequential" problems, serves in a similar manner to study the **NC** = **P** question.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] Finding an efficient way to parallelize the solution to some **P**-complete problem would show that **NC** = **P**.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] It can also be thought of as the "problems requiring superlogarithmic space"; a log-space solution to a **P**-complete problem (using the definition based on log-space reductions) would imply **L** = **P**.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] The logic behind this is analogous to the logic that a polynomial-time solution to an **NP**-complete problem would prove **P** = **NP**: if we have a **NC** reduction from any problem in **P** to a problem *A*, and an **NC** solution for *A*, then **NC** = **P**.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] Similarly, if we have a log-space reduction from any problem in **P** to a problem *A*, and a log-space solution for *A*, then **L** = **P**.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] There are many different many-one reductions used when defining **P**-completeness, with variable strengths.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] At the lowest level is **NC**1-reduction, then **L**-reduction, then **NC**2-reduction, **NC**3-reduction, and so on.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] For **NC***k*-reduction and **NC**-reduction, uniformity is imposed, because the intention of **P**-completeness theory is to prove upper bounds.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] Non-uniformity is useful for proving lower bounds, but for upper bounds, non-uniformity is unsatisfactory, since they are too powerful for this purpose.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] The standard uniformity condition is **L**-uniformity, meaning that the circuit family should be constructable by a Turing machine, such that given $1^{n}$ as input, it outputs a description of the n -th circuit using $O(\log n)$ working tape.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] Given two languages $L,L'$ , define $L\leq _{m}^{{\mathsf {NC}}^{k}}L'$ if and only if there exists a **L**-uniform **NC***k* Boolean circuit family that together computes a function $f:\{0,1\}^{*}\to \{0,1\}^{*}$ , such that $x\in L$ if and only if $f(x)\in L'$ .
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] Define $L\leq _{m}^{\mathsf {L}}L'$ if and only if there exists a function $f:\{0,1\}^{*}\to \{0,1\}^{*}$ that is implicitly logspace computable, such that $x\in L$ if and only if $f(x)\in L'$ .
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] Define a language L in **P** to be **P**-complete relative to **NC***k*-reduction if and only if for any language $L'$ in **P**, $L'\leq _{m}^{{\mathsf {NC}}^{k}}L$ .
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] Usually for **P**-completeness, **NC**-reduction is meant by default, though many results in the literature concerning **P**-completeness still holds even under the strongest assumption of **NC**1-reduction.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] The most basic **P**-complete problem under logspace many-one reductions is the following: given a Turing machine M , an input for that machine *x*, and a number *T* (written in unary), $\langle M,x,T\rangle$ does that machine halt on that input within the first *T* steps?
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] To reduce an $L\in {\mathsf {P}}$ to this problem, take a Turing Machine $M_{L}$ deciding L in time bounded by the polynomial *p*.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] Then for any $x\in L$ , output the encoding of $M_{L}$ , the encoding of *x* itself, and a number of steps $T=p(|x|)$ .
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] The machine *M* halts on *x* within $p(|x|)$ steps if and only if *x* is in *L*.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] Clearly, if we can parallelize a general simulation of a sequential computer (i.e. the Turing machine simulation of Turing machines), then we will be able to parallelize any program that runs on that computer.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] If this problem is in **NC**, then so is every other problem in **P**.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] If the number of steps is written in binary, the problem is EXPTIME-complete.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] This problem illustrates a common trick in the theory of **P**-completeness.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] We aren't really interested in whether a problem can be solved quickly on a parallel machine.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] We're just interested in whether a parallel machine solves it *much more* quickly than a sequential machine.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] Therefore, we have to reword the problem so that the sequential version is in **P**.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] That is why this problem required *T* to be written in unary.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] If a number *T* is written as a binary number (a string of *n* ones and zeros, where *n* = log *T*), then the obvious sequential algorithm can take time 2*n*.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] On the other hand, if *T* is written as a unary number (a string of *n* ones, where *n* = *T*), then it only takes time *n*.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] By writing *T* in unary rather than binary, we have reduced the obvious sequential algorithm from exponential time to linear time.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] That puts the sequential problem in **P**.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] Then, it will be in **NC** if and only if it is parallelizable.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] Many other problems have been proved to be **P**-complete, and therefore are widely believed to be inherently sequential.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] Most of the languages above are **P**-complete under even stronger notions of reduction, such as uniform $AC^{0}$ many-one reductions, DLOGTIME reductions, or polylogarithmic projections.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] In order to prove that a given problem in **P** is **P**-complete, one typically tries to reduce a known **P**-complete problem to the given one.
[src:parallel-complexity/p-complete] Sivakumar, building on work by Ogihara, showed that if there exists a sparse language that is **P**-complete, then **L** = **P**.
[src:parallel-complexity/parallel-ram] In computer science, a **parallel random-access machine** (**parallel RAM** or **PRAM**) is a shared-memory abstract machine.
[src:parallel-complexity/parallel-ram] As its name indicates, the PRAM is intended as the parallel-computing analogy to the random-access machine (RAM) (not to be confused with random-access memory).
[src:parallel-complexity/parallel-ram] Similar to the way in which the RAM model neglects practical issues, such as access time to cache memory versus main memory, the PRAM model neglects such issues as synchronization and communication, but provides any (problem-size-dependent) number of processors.
[src:parallel-complexity/parallel-ram] Algorithm cost, for instance, is estimated using two parameters O(time) and O(time × processor_number).
[src:parallel-complexity/parallel-ram] Concurrent read concurrent write (CRCW)—multiple processors can read and write.
[src:parallel-complexity/parallel-ram] A CRCW PRAM is sometimes called a **concurrent random-access machine**.
[src:parallel-complexity/parallel-ram] Here, E and C stand for 'exclusive' and 'concurrent' respectively.
[src:parallel-complexity/parallel-ram] Several simplifying assumptions are made while considering the development of algorithms for PRAM.
[src:parallel-complexity/parallel-ram] Any memory location is uniformly accessible from any processor.
[src:parallel-complexity/parallel-ram] There is no limit on the amount of shared memory in the system.
[src:parallel-complexity/parallel-ram] The programs written on these machines are, in general, of type SIMD.
[src:parallel-complexity/parallel-ram] These kinds of algorithms are useful for understanding the exploitation of concurrency, dividing the original problem into similar sub-problems and solving them in parallel.
[src:parallel-complexity/parallel-ram] The introduction of the formal 'P-RAM' model in Wyllie's 1979 thesis had the aim of quantifying analysis of parallel algorithms in a way analogous to the Turing Machine.
[src:parallel-complexity/parallel-ram] The analysis focused on a MIMD model of programming using a CREW model but showed that many variants, including implementing a CRCW model and implementing on an SIMD machine, were possible with only constant overhead.
[src:parallel-complexity/parallel-ram] However, the test for practical relevance of PRAM (or RAM) algorithms depends on whether their cost model provides an effective abstraction of some computer; the structure of that computer can be quite different than the abstract model.
[src:parallel-complexity/parallel-ram] The knowledge of the layers of software and hardware that need to be inserted is beyond the scope of this article.
[src:parallel-complexity/parallel-ram] The article Ghanim, Vishkin & Barua (2018) demonstrated that PRAM algorithms as-is can achieve competitive performance even without any additional effort to cast them as multi-threaded programs on XMT.
[src:parallel-complexity/parallel-ram] This is an example of SystemVerilog code which finds the maximum value in the array in only 2 clock cycles.
[src:parallel-complexity/parallel-ram] It compares all the combinations of the elements in the array at the first clock, and merges the result at the second clock.
[src:parallel-complexity/parallel-ram] It uses CRCW memory; `m[i] <= 1` and `maxNo <= data[i]` are written concurrently.
[src:parallel-complexity/parallel-ram] The concurrency causes no conflicts because the algorithm guarantees that the same value is written to the same memory.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] In computer architecture, **speedup** is a number that measures the relative performance of two systems processing the same problem.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] More technically, it is the improvement in speed of execution of a task executed on two similar architectures with different resources.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] The notion of speedup was established by Amdahl's law, which was particularly focused on parallel processing.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] However, speedup can be used more generally to show the effect on performance after any resource enhancement.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] Speedup can be defined for two different types of quantities: *latency* and *throughput*.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] Latency is often measured in seconds per unit of execution workload.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] Throughput is often measured in units of execution workload per second.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] Another unit of throughput is instructions per cycle (IPC) and its reciprocal, cycles per instruction (CPI), is another unit of latency.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] Speedup is dimensionless and defined differently for each type of quantity so that it is a consistent metric.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] Speedup in latency can be predicted from Amdahl's law or Gustafson's law.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] We are testing the effectiveness of a branch predictor on the execution of a program.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] First, we execute the program with the standard branch predictor on the processor, which yields an execution time of 6.75 seconds.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] Next, we execute the program with our modified (and hopefully improved) branch predictor on the same processor, which produces an execution time of 4.50 seconds.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] In both cases the execution workload is the same.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] Our new branch predictor has provided a 1.5x speedup over the original.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] We can also measure speedup in cycles per instruction (CPI) which is a latency.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] First, we execute the program with the standard branch predictor, which yields a CPI of 3.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] Next, we execute the program with our modified branch predictor, which yields a CPI of 2.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] In both cases the execution workload is the same and both architectures are not pipelined nor parallel.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] We can also measure speedup in instructions per cycle (IPC), which is a throughput and the inverse of CPI.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] We achieve the same 1.5x speedup, though we measured different quantities.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] Let *S* be the speedup of execution of a task and *s* the speedup of execution of the part of the task that benefits from the improvement of the resources of an architecture.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] *Linear speedup* or *ideal speedup* is obtained when *S* = *s*.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] When running a task with linear speedup, doubling the local speedup doubles the overall speedup.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] As this is ideal, it is considered very good scalability.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] Programs with linear speedup and programs running on a single processor have an efficiency of 1, while many difficult-to-parallelize programs have efficiency such as 1/ln(*s*) that approaches 0 as the number of processors *A* = *s* increases.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] In marketing contexts, speedup curves are more often used, largely because they go up and to the right and thus appear better to the less-informed.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] Sometimes a speedup of more than *A* when using *A* processors is observed in parallel computing, which is called *super-linear speedup*.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] Super-linear speedup rarely happens and often confuses beginners, who believe the theoretical maximum speedup should be *A* when *A* processors are used.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] One possible reason for super-linear speedup in low-level computations is the cache effect resulting from the different memory hierarchies of a modern computer: in parallel computing, not only do the numbers of processors change, but so does the size of accumulated caches from different processors.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] With the larger accumulated cache size, more or even all of the working set can fit into caches and the memory access time reduces dramatically, which causes the extra speedup in addition to that from the actual computation.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] An analogous situation occurs when searching large datasets, such as the genomic data searched by BLAST implementations.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] There the accumulated RAM from each of the nodes in a cluster enables the dataset to move from disk into RAM thereby drastically reducing the time required by e.g. mpiBLAST to search it.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] Super-linear speedups can also occur when performing backtracking in parallel: an exception in one thread can cause several other threads to backtrack early, before they reach the exception themselves.
[src:parallel-complexity/speedup] Super-linear speedups can also occur in parallel implementations of branch-and-bound for optimization: the processing of one node by one processor may affect the work other processors need to do for the other nodes.
